<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-662-096  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 662 096.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 23 1990 v24 n30 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC aims to cut overseas rates. (Federal CommunicationsCommission)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Horwitt, Elisabeth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) plans to reduce therates for international telephone service by as much as 50percent.andP;  The FCC plan involves the streamlining of the process ofreductions in international accounting rates for US carriers.andP;  Itmay also include the establishment of lower, cost-based accountingrates for international traffic.andP;  While competition has driveninternational traffic downward, the monopolistic control overtelecommunications services enjoyed by many foreigntelecommunications authorities have kept the cost of placing callsto the US at about three times the cost of a comparable US-basedcall.andP;  This disparity has caused an increase in the US' networksettlements deficit from $40 million in 1979 to $2 billion in1988.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TelecommunicationsUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionGovernment RegulationCommunications Service SuppliersTelephone CompaniesCost of CommunicationsForeign Competition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>